WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.600 --> 00:00:06.440
Sand. It's being smuggled
on a global scale.

00:00:06.440 --> 00:00:09.120
There are many billions
of dollars worth

00:00:09.120 --> 00:00:12.440
of sand being dug up
and sold illegally every year.

00:00:12.440 --> 00:00:14.840
It's cheap and easy to extract.

00:00:14.840 --> 00:00:18.640
It is a low risk,
high reward business.

00:00:18.640 --> 00:00:24.160
Sometimes involving criminal gangs,
violence, even murder.

00:00:24.160 --> 00:00:29.440
My complaints were not taken seriously
until I got attacked by the sand mafia.

00:00:32.360 --> 00:00:35.160
So why is sand in such high demand?

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:40.800
The modern world is made of it.

00:00:40.800 --> 00:00:45.120
Sand is in concrete,
asphalt, glass and silicon.

00:00:45.120 --> 00:00:48.760
It even turns up
in places you wouldn't expect.

00:00:48.760 --> 00:00:53.320
We use sand in cosmetics,
in certain kinds of wine,

00:00:53.320 --> 00:00:58.280
we use sand in paint,
we use sand to make elastics.

00:00:58.280 --> 00:01:02.320
Around 50 billion tons of sand
and gravel are used every year.

00:01:02.320 --> 00:01:04.560
That's enough to cover the whole
of Argentina

00:01:04.560 --> 00:01:07.320
in a layer one centimetre thick.

00:01:09.040 --> 00:01:15.160
90% of all the sand mined
goes into the construction industry.

00:01:15.160 --> 00:01:18.880
China and India
are the biggest consumers.

00:01:18.880 --> 00:01:23.040
All over the developing world.
Hundreds of millions of people

00:01:23.040 --> 00:01:28.000
are moving from the countryside
into cities every year.

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:32.840
So worldwide, we are building the
equivalent of nine New York cities

00:01:32.840 --> 00:01:35.360
every single year.

00:01:37.360 --> 00:01:41.440
And not all of the world's sand
can be used for construction,

00:01:43.440 --> 00:01:46.400
desert sands eroded by wind
are round.

00:01:46.400 --> 00:01:50.800
The best sand for concrete has
jagged edges and comes from rivers,

00:01:52.480 --> 00:01:58.240
this shape helps it bind together,
making it strong and durable.

00:01:58.240 --> 00:02:01.480
Sand is taken from riverbeds by hand
or by dredges,

00:02:01.480 --> 00:02:06.160
and more is being extracted
than can naturally be replenished.

00:02:06.160 --> 00:02:09.360
Sand, which is the second
most extracted material in the world

00:02:09.360 --> 00:02:13.320
after water, is in short supply.

00:02:13.320 --> 00:02:17.760
Globally, the sand market is worth
around $165 billion,

00:02:17.760 --> 00:02:23.200
but it's nearly impossible to know how
much of that has been sourced illegally.

00:02:23.200 --> 00:02:27.240
The estimates range anywhere, you know,
up into the tens of billions of dollars.

00:02:27.240 --> 00:02:31.960
We know for sure
that there's illegal sand mining
in dozens and dozens of countries.

00:02:31.960 --> 00:02:36.840
That happens in Western Europe and North
America on a relatively small scale,

00:02:36.840 --> 00:02:41.520
and it happens in the developing world
on like a millions of tonne scale.

00:02:41.520 --> 00:02:43.680
Researchers estimate that
in these countries,

00:02:43.680 --> 00:02:47.080
more than 50% of sand mining
is illegal,

00:02:47.080 --> 00:02:51.680
but no organization tracks sand,
so there isn't international data.

00:02:51.680 --> 00:02:56.080
In The Gambia, a one off Interpol
operation targeting illegal activity

00:02:56.080 --> 00:03:00.320
found unprecedented levels
of illicit sand mining.

00:03:00.320 --> 00:03:07.080
This is all dredged sand from
the seaside, huge mountains of sand.

00:03:07.080 --> 00:03:10.680
Illegal mining means sand is removed
without proper authorization

00:03:10.680 --> 00:03:15.480
or from prohibited areas.
And once it's mixed with legal sand,

00:03:15.480 --> 00:03:18.720
it's almost impossible
to tell the difference.

00:03:18.720 --> 00:03:20.920
It can be transported
to a construction site

00:03:20.920 --> 00:03:24.360
and no one knows where it came from,
and nobody asked questions.

00:03:24.360 --> 00:03:31.520
It can be moved on a container ship and
nobody knows where the source of it is.

00:03:31.520 --> 00:03:32.680
Ease of extraction,

00:03:32.680 --> 00:03:36.400
high demand for concrete, and
the fact that sand is legal to buy

00:03:36.400 --> 00:03:40.680
and sell mean that illegal mining
continues with little opposition.

00:03:40.680 --> 00:03:42.120
Sand is a free commodity.

00:03:42.120 --> 00:03:46.560
Anybody who is strong enough,
powerful enough can go and collect sand.

00:03:46.560 --> 00:03:50.280
And it's often at the local level
where exploitation starts and

00:03:50.280 --> 00:03:52.800
where so-called sand mafias operate.

00:03:52.800 --> 00:03:57.960
It can be either a small villager
who's taking sand from the beach
to build his own house,

00:03:57.960 --> 00:04:01.160
right up to the point
where people who have taken sand

00:04:01.160 --> 00:04:07.840
and realized how lucrative it is have
risen and formed networks and gangs.

00:04:07.840 --> 00:04:12.200
This is usually possible
through bribery or intimidation.

00:04:12.200 --> 00:04:18.600
There is just major corruption of local
and regional governments in sand mining

00:04:18.600 --> 00:04:26.200
because there's very little capacity
to enforce prohibitions.

00:04:26.200 --> 00:04:28.920
Criminal activity,
including sand mafias,

00:04:28.920 --> 00:04:32.920
are making headlines
as illegal mining turns violent.

00:04:34.680 --> 00:04:39.720
Hundreds of people have been murdered
over sand just in the last few years,

00:04:39.720 --> 00:04:42.480
and that's been, I mean,
there's documented cases

00:04:42.480 --> 00:04:47.120
of this happening in Mexico,
in Ghana, in Indonesia,

00:04:47.120 --> 00:04:51.280
in many, many countries around
the world, and especially in India.

00:04:51.280 --> 00:04:54.840
I was attacked
in 2004 by sand miners,

00:04:54.840 --> 00:04:59.560
and that's when it became
more serious and more intense for me.

00:04:59.560 --> 00:05:03.080
Since then, Sumaira has been campaigning
against illegal sand mining

00:05:03.080 --> 00:05:08.000
and highlighting the effect it's
having in India and around the world.

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:11.600
Well, if your houses are washed away,
it impacts you immediately.

00:05:11.600 --> 00:05:14.480
Even without a catastrophe
like a flood,

00:05:14.480 --> 00:05:20.160
you can see the effects because you
can see the erosion on a daily basis.

00:05:20.160 --> 00:05:25.120
Over mining of rivers and beaches
means there's a greater risk
of landslides and flooding,

00:05:25.120 --> 00:05:30.360
while dredging has significant
consequences for fragile ecosystems.

00:05:30.360 --> 00:05:34.160
When you when you do that, when
you suck up the bottom of a river,

00:05:34.160 --> 00:05:36.440
obviously whatever was living
down there,

00:05:36.440 --> 00:05:39.560
whatever kind of fish and plant life
were living on that riverbed,

00:05:39.560 --> 00:05:43.360
you've just annihilated
their habitat, wiped it out.

00:05:43.360 --> 00:05:45.920
New technologies could help.

00:05:45.920 --> 00:05:48.280
More concrete than ever
is being recycled,

00:05:48.280 --> 00:05:51.800
and sand can be created artificially
by crushing rocks.

00:05:51.800 --> 00:05:57.360
But manufacturing is expensive,
and both are energy intensive.

00:05:57.360 --> 00:06:00.880
And as long as extracting sand
remains cheap and plentiful,

00:06:00.880 --> 00:06:04.480
cracking down
on sand smuggling won't be easy.

00:06:04.480 --> 00:06:08.240
You need to have
communities much more involved

00:06:08.240 --> 00:06:11.280
in monitoring illegal sand mining,

00:06:11.280 --> 00:06:14.040
you've got
to be addressing the corruption,

00:06:14.040 --> 00:06:15.880
you need to raise awareness.

00:06:15.880 --> 00:06:21.080
And because nobody is paying
adequate attention to it, it goes on

00:06:21.080 --> 00:06:23.760
and the devastation continues.

